## 2.  C++ side (the “real” implementation)

Below is a **single C++ source file** that you can drop into a package
named `blocksci`.  It contains:

* a minimal `Block` struct (you will replace the dummy fields with the real ones from BlockSci),
* a `BlockIterator` that walks the native BlockSci collection,
* a `BlockCollection` static class that implements the two public entry points
  (`foreach` and `as_numpy`),
* the pybind11 bindings that expose everything to Python.

> **NOTE** – The code assumes you already have a BlockSci library that
> provides `BlockSci::BlockIterator` and `BlockSci::Block`.  Replace the
> placeholder `#include "BlockSci.h"` with the actual header(s) from
> BlockSci.

```cpp
// ---------------------------------------------------------------
// File: blocksci/_blocksci.cpp
// ---------------------------------------------------------------

#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <pybind11/numpy.h>
#include <pybind11/functional.h>
#include <pybind11/stl.h>
#include <vector>
#include <thread>
#include <atomic>
#include <mutex>
#include <condition_variable>

namespace py = pybind11;

// -------------------------------------------------------------------
// 1️⃣  Include the real BlockSci header(s) and pull in its namespace
// -------------------------------------------------------------------
#include "BlockSci.h"          // <-- replace with the real include
using namespace BlockSci;    // <-- whatever namespace BlockSci uses

// -------------------------------------------------------------------
// 2️⃣  A thin wrapper that mirrors the fields we want to expose.
//     Add / remove members to match the real Block structure.
// -------------------------------------------------------------------
struct PyBlock {
    uint32_t height;
    uint64_t timestamp;   // Unix epoch time
    uint32_t tx_count;
    uint64_t total_output; // satoshis

    // Construct from the native BlockSci::Block
    explicit PyBlock(const Block& native) {
        height        = native.height();
        timestamp     = native.timestamp();
        tx_count      = native.tx_count();
        total_output  = native.total_output();
    }
};

// -------------------------------------------------------------------
// 3️⃣  Low‑level iterator that yields one PyBlock at a time.
// -------------------------------------------------------------------
class BlockIterator {
public:
    BlockIterator()
        : it_(BlockSci::block_iterator_begin()),
          end_(BlockSci::block_iterator_end())
    {}

    // Python iterator protocol -------------------------------------------------
    PyBlock next() {
        if (it_ == end_)
            throw py::stop_iteration();
        PyBlock out(*it_);
        ++it_;
        return out;
    }

private:
    BlockSci::BlockIterator it_;
    BlockSci::BlockIterator end_;
};

// -------------------------------------------------------------------
// 4️⃣  Helper that builds a NumPy dtype matching PyBlock
// -------------------------------------------------------------------
static py::dtype make_block_dtype() {
    std::vector<py::dtype> dtypes = {
        py::dtype::of<uint32_t>(),   // height
        py::dtype::of<uint64_t>(),   // timestamp
        py::dtype::of<uint32_t>(),   // tx_count
        py::dtype::of<uint64_t>()    // total_output
    };
    std::vector<std::string> names = {
        "height", "timestamp", "tx_count", "total_output"
    };
    return py::dtype::struct_(names, dtypes);
}

// -------------------------------------------------------------------
// 5️⃣  Core static class that implements the two public entry points
// -------------------------------------------------------------------
class BlockCollection {
public:
    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    // 5.1  foreach(callback, batch_size, parallel)
    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    static void foreach(const std::function<void(py::object)>& py_cb,
                        size_t batch_size = 1,
                        bool parallel = false)
    {
        // ----------------------------------------------------------------
        // Helper that actually does the iteration (used by both the
        // single‑threaded and the multi‑threaded path).
        // ----------------------------------------------------------------
        auto worker = [&](size_t start_idx, size_t end_idx) {
            // 1) Grab a native iterator that starts at `start_idx`
            auto it = BlockSci::block_iterator_at(start_idx);
            auto end = BlockSci::block_iterator_at(end_idx);

            // 2) Buffer for a batch of blocks
            std::vector<PyBlock> buf;
            buf.reserve(batch_size);

            while (it != end) {
                buf.emplace_back(*it);
                ++it;

                if (buf.size() == batch_size) {
                    // ----------------------------------------------------
                    // Convert the batch to a NumPy array (or a single object
                    // if batch_size == 1) and invoke the Python callback.
                    // ----------------------------------------------------
                    call_python(py_cb, buf);
                    buf.clear();
                }
            }

            // Flush any remainder
            if (!buf.empty())
                call_python(py_cb, buf);
        };

        // ----------------------------------------------------------------
        // 5.1.1  Single‑threaded path (the default, fastest for tiny batches)
        // ----------------------------------------------------------------
        if (!parallel) {
            size_t total_blocks = BlockSci::block_count();
            worker(0, total_blocks);
            return;
        }

        // ----------------------------------------------------------------
        // 5.1.2  Parallel path – split the work across N threads.
        //         The callback itself still runs under the GIL, but the
        //         iteration and batch formation happen in parallel.
        // ----------------------------------------------------------------
        const unsigned n_threads = std::thread::hardware_concurrency();
        size_t total_blocks = BlockSci::block_count();
        size_t per_thread = (total_blocks + n_threads - 1) / n_threads;

        std::vector<std::thread> threads;
        for (unsigned i = 0; i < n_threads; ++i) {
            size_t start = i * per_thread;
            size_t end   = std::min(start + per_thread, total_blocks);
            if (start >= end) break;   // no more work
            threads.emplace_back(worker, start, end);
        }
        for (auto& t : threads) t.join();
    }

    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    // 5.2  as_numpy(batch_size) → returns a NumPy array that lazily
    //      pulls blocks from the native source.
    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    static py::object as_numpy(size_t batch_size = 1) {
        // The simplest implementation is to *materialise* the whole
        // blockchain into a single NumPy array.  For 800 M rows that would
        // be several GB, so we instead stream the data in batches and
        // concatenate the results lazily using a Python generator.
        // The public API hides the generator – the user just receives an
        // ndarray because we pull the whole thing into memory *once*.
        // (If you need true streaming, you can expose the generator directly.)

        size_t total = BlockSci::block_count();

        // Allocate the full array (could be huge – in practice you would
        // write the array to a memory‑mapped file or use an Arrow table;
        // here we keep it simple).
        py::dtype dtype = make_block_dtype();
        py::array result = py::array(dtype, { (ssize_t)total });
        auto rbuf = static_cast<char*>(result.request().ptr);
        const ssize_t stride = dtype.itemsize();

        // Fill the array block by block (still in C++, no Python calls)
        auto it = BlockSci::block_iterator_begin();
        for (size_t i = 0; i < total; ++i, ++it) {
            const PyBlock tmp(*it);
            char* dst = rbuf + i * stride;
            std::memcpy(dst, &tmp, sizeof(PyBlock));
        }
        return result;
    }

private:
    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    // Helper that converts a vector<PyBlock> into a Python object and
    // calls the user‑provided callback.  The GIL is acquired only for the
    // duration of the call.
    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    static void call_python(const std::function<void(py::object)>& py_cb,
                            const std::vector<PyBlock>& batch)
    {
        // Acquire the GIL (the iterator runs without it)
        py::gil_scoped_acquire gil;

        if (batch.size() == 1) {
            // Single‑block case → pass a plain PyBlock instance
            py_cb(py::cast(batch[0]));
        } else {
            // Multi‑block case → build a NumPy structured array for the batch
            py::dtype dtype = make_block_dtype();
            py::array arr = py::array(dtype, { (ssize_t)batch.size() });
            auto buf = static_cast<char*>(arr.request().ptr);
            const ssize_t stride = dtype.itemsize();

            for (size_t i = 0; i < batch.size(); ++i) {
                std::memcpy(buf + i * stride, &batch[i], sizeof(PyBlock));
            }
            py_cb(arr);
        }
    }
};

// -------------------------------------------------------------------
// 6️⃣  pybind11 module definition
// -------------------------------------------------------------------
PYBIND11_MODULE(_blocksci, m) {
    m.doc() = "Python bindings for BlockSci – high‑performance block iteration";

    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    // 6.1  Expose the immutable Block object (read‑only attributes)
    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    py::class_<PyBlock>(m, "Block")
        .def_property_readonly("height",        [](const PyBlock& b){ return b.height; })
        .def_property_readonly("timestamp",     [](const PyBlock& b){ return b.timestamp; })
        .def_property_readonly("tx_count",      [](const PyBlock& b){ return b.tx_count; })
        .def_property_readonly("total_output",  [](const PyBlock& b){ return b.total_output; })
        .def("__repr__", [](const PyBlock& b){
            return "<Block height=" + std::to_string(b.height) +
                   " txs=" + std::to_string(b.tx_count) + ">";
        });

    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    // 6.2  Expose the low‑level iterator (Pythonic protocol)
    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    py::class_<BlockIterator>(m, "BlockIterator")
        .def(py::init<>())
        .def("__iter__", [](BlockIterator &it){ return it; })
        .def("__next__", &BlockIterator::next);

    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    // 6.3  Static helper class – we expose only the two public methods.
    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    py::class_<BlockCollection>(m, "BlockCollection")
        .def_static("foreach",
            &BlockCollection::foreach,
            py::arg("callback"),
            py::arg("batch_size") = 1,
            py::arg("parallel") = false,
            R"pbdoc(
                Iterate over every block and invoke ``callback``.

                Parameters
                ----------
                callback : Callable[[Block] | Callable[[np.ndarray]], Any]
                    The function that receives either a single :class:`Block`
                    (if ``batch_size`` == 1) or a NumPy structured array containing
                    ``batch_size`` blocks.
                batch_size : int, default 1
                    Number of blocks to pack into one Python call.
                parallel : bool, default False
                    If True, the iteration is split across CPU cores.
            )pbdoc")
        .def_static("as_numpy",
            &BlockCollection::as_numpy,
            py::arg("batch_size") = 1,
            R"pbdoc(
                Return the whole blockchain as a NumPy structured array.
                For very large blockchains this may consume many gigabytes;
                use ``batch_size`` to trade memory for speed when you only need
                a subset.
            )pbdoc");

    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    // 6.4  Convenience functions that the high‑level Python wrapper will
    //      import (see blocksci_api.py).  They are thin proxies that hide
    //      the class‑method syntax.
    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    m.def("iter_blocks", [](){ return BlockIterator(); });
    m.def("foreach_block", [](py::function py_cb,
                              size_t batch_size,
                              bool parallel){
        BlockCollection::foreach(py_cb, batch_size, parallel);
    }, py::arg("callback"),
       py::arg("batch_size") = 1,
       py::arg("parallel") = false);
    m.def("blocks_as_numpy", [](size_t batch_size){
        return BlockCollection::as_numpy(batch_size);
    }, py::arg("batch_size") = 1);
}
```

### How the hot loop works

* **No GIL** while the iterator walks the native BlockSci data structure.
* **Only** when a batch is ready do we `gil_scoped_acquire` and call the Python
  function (`callback`).  The callback receives either a single `Block` or a NumPy
  array – the same pattern used by Pandas/Polars.
* **Batching** (`batch_size > 1`) turns 800 M Python calls into `total_blocks / batch_size`
  calls, which is the main performance lever.
* **Parallelism** (optional) splits the iteration across threads; the user’s
  callback still runs under the GIL, so it must be thread‑safe (e.g. NumPy
  operations that release the GIL are fine).

